hands_on_practices.problem:
A layer $5$ pyramidal neuron’s apical dendrite can be approximated as a uniform, passive, cylindrical cable for small-signal propagation relevant to the envelope of a back-propagating action potential (bAP) or the spread preceding a dendritic sodium ($\text{Na}^{+}$) or calcium ($\text{Ca}^{2+}$) spike. Assume the membrane is ohmic and linearized around rest, and consider steady state (time-invariant) conditions so that capacitive currents vanish. The dendrite is semi-infinite, with the proximal end at $x=0$ held at a fixed depolarization relative to rest. 

Starting from current conservation and Ohm’s law along the cable, use the definitions of membrane resistance per unit length and axial resistance per unit length in terms of specific membrane resistance $R_{m}$ and axial resistivity $R_{a}$ for a cylinder of diameter $d$ to:
- derive the steady-state cable equation and its general solution for $V(x)$ on a semi-infinite cable;
- obtain the space (length) constant $\lambda$ as a function of $R_{m}$, $R_{a}$, and $d$;
- evaluate the attenuation ratio $V(x)/V(0)$ at position $x$.

Use the following biophysical parameters for the dendrite: specific membrane resistance $R_{m}=30\,\text{k}\Omega\cdot\text{cm}^{2}$, axial resistivity $R_{a}=150\,\Omega\cdot\text{cm}$, diameter $d=2\,\mu\text{m}$, and position $x=300\,\mu\text{m}$. Express the final attenuation ratio $V(x)/V(0)$ as a dimensionless number and round your answer to four significant figures.
